  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Let me clarify the acknowledgement approach for both Go-Back-N (GBN) and Selective Repeat (SR) ARQ protocols:\n\nGo-Back-N (GBN) ARQ:\n- Uses cumulative acknowledgements\n- When an ACK is received for packet N, it means all packets up to and including N have been correctly received\n- If a packet is lost or corrupted, the receiver discards all subsequent packets and requests retransmission of the lost packet\n- The sender must retransmit all packets from the lost packet onwards\n\nSelective Repeat (SR) ARQ:\n- Uses individual acknowledgements for each packet\n- Each packet is acknowledged separately\n- Only the specific lost or corrupted packets are retransmitted\n- Allows for more efficient use of the transmission channel compared to GBN\n\nSo in summary:\n- GBN: Cumulative acknowledgements\n- SR: Individual packet acknowledgements",
